english:
  title: 'Blue Words: Three Libations at the Altar of Chamseongdan on Mani Mountain'
  author: Byeon Gye-ryang
  language: eng
  text: |-
    FIRST LIBATION

    In the waning spring, we choose an auspicious day
    and solemnly spread this altar of communion.
    Though our offerings are meager,
    we lift them toward the divine gaze—
    with humble sincerity we present ourselves,
    kneeling to receive your true descent.

    SECOND LIBATION

    The Way of the Three Pure Ones dwells in mystery,
    far and faint, difficult to comprehend.
    Yet we pour forth our deepest reverence,
    and swiftly comes your response.
    We beseech you: accept our worship,
    and hold us steadfast in your protection.

    THIRD LIBATION

    The mountain floats upon the sea,
    remote from the dust of the mortal realm;
    the altar rises among the clouds,
    a fitting place for celestial chariots to arrive.
    Now we labor in devotion's service,
    asking that you draw near and guide us.

    We reflect: that one so insignificant
    should bear so grave and weighty a trust—
    truly humbling. You shine, radiant and eternal;
    we know that Heaven's mandate is not fixed
    to any one forever. In trembling awe,
    how dare we forget that rulership is arduous?

    So do we reverence with utmost depth,
    our eyes ever turned toward your brightness.
    We offer now this simple, purified form,
    asking for your unseen blessing.
    Pierc through to the truth within our hearts;
    let your benevolent grace pour down.

    May all the calamities foretold in the eight trigrams
    be forever erased and dispelled.
    Grant us peace and joy ahead;
    preserve the great blessings of the Book of Changes.
    Letlongevity flourish and vitality endure;
    let warfare cease and the age know harmony;
    let harvests abound and all things thrive.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Chamseongdan (參聖壇) is an ancient stone altar on Mani Mountain (摩利山) in Korea, traditionally associated with Dangun, the legendary founder of Gojoseon.
  - key: ''
    value: The Three Pure Ones (三清) refer to the highest deities in religious Daoism, representing different aspects of the Dao.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'eight trigrams' (箕範) and 'Book of Changes' (羲經) reference classical Chinese cosmological and divinatory texts that influenced East Asian thought.
  - key: ''
    value: This is a formal liturgical text composed for a state or elite religious ceremony, employing classical parallelism and elevated register throughout.
